      "In mainstream psychology, neuroscience, and trauma studies, trauma is understood not only as an event, but as a nervous-system adaptation to threat. When individuals or groups experience chronic stress, violence, instability, or humiliation, the nervous system learns patterns of hypervigilance, shutdown, or reactive behavior. These patterns persist long after the original threat has passed, shaping perception, emotion, and decision-making.\n\nModern research shows that trauma affects memory, attention, and meaning-making. Under stress, the brain prioritizes survival over nuance, leading to black-and-white thinking, emotional reactivity, and difficulty integrating new information. Importantly, trauma responses are not moral failures; they are learned protections. Decolonizing at this level means recognizing when a response is driven by present evidence versus past conditioning—and learning to regulate the body so the mind can re-engage choice.",
