  core: {
    L1:
      "In mainstream media studies and communication theory, media is understood as a meaning-making system rather than a neutral channel. News cycles, social platforms, algorithms, and entertainment industries shape attention by selecting what is visible, urgent, and emotionally charged. Repetition, speed, and framing determine which narratives feel real and which fade into the background.\n\nModern media environments prioritize engagement. This means stories that provoke fear, outrage, identity affirmation, or moral certainty are amplified, while slower, complex, or context-heavy analysis is often deprioritized. Over time, this trains audiences to expect immediacy and emotional clarity rather than nuance. Myth enters when simplified narratives are repeated so often that they become taken-for-granted truths. Decolonizing media literacy involves slowing down consumption, identifying incentives, and separating evidence from emotional packaging.",
    L2:
      "From Afro-Indigenous perspectives, storytelling has always been recognized as a technology. Stories transmit values, memory, warning, and instruction. Traditional systems place responsibility on storytellers to maintain balance and on listeners to engage with discernment. Myth, in this sense, is not falsehood; it is symbolic compression—meaning layered into narrative form.\n\nProblems arise when modern story machines strip responsibility from storytelling while retaining its influence. Entertainment and news can detach story from consequence, turning suffering into spectacle and complexity into caricature. Decolonization here means reclaiming the elder skill of listening beneath the surface: What lesson is being taught? What behavior is being normalized? What identity is being rewarded? When stories are re-embedded in ethical context, myth becomes guidance again rather than manipulation.",
    L3:
      "Power patterns are especially concentrated in media systems:\n\nMYTHOLOGIZE: Repeating simplified stories until they feel timeless and unquestionable.\n\nSANITIZE: Removing structural causes from narratives, focusing on personalities or isolated incidents.\n\nLAUNDER_ATTRIB: Crediting outcomes to ‘public opinion,’ ‘trends,’ or ‘culture’ instead of algorithmic and corporate incentives.\n\nERASE: Excluding historical context and alternative viewpoints that would complicate the story.\n\nMILITARIZE: Framing issues as battles—us vs. them—to lock audiences into emotional allegiance.\n\nWhen media becomes the primary teacher, populations can confuse familiarity with truth. Decolonization does not require abandoning media; it requires rebalancing. You learn to consume stories intentionally, cross-check claims, and notice how emotion is being used to guide interpretation. The goal is not detachment, but agency—the ability to engage stories without being absorbed by them.",
  },
  practice:
    "Action (15 minutes): Choose one media source you consume daily. Track three stories from it in a single day. For each, note: (1) the emotion it evokes, (2) the main lesson or takeaway, and (3) one piece of context that is missing but relevant.\n\nOptional upgrade: Take a 24-hour pause from reactive media (breaking news, outrage-driven feeds) and observe how your attention and mood shift.",
  journal:
    "Which stories or narratives have shaped how you see the world the most? How might your perception change if you slowed down or diversified your media diet?",
