      "From Afro-Indigenous perspectives, law traditionally emerges from relationship rather than abstraction. Order is maintained through customs, councils, elders, restorative practices, and shared responsibility. Justice is measured by restoration of balance, not simply punishment. Authority is situational and accountable to the community.\n\nColonial empires disrupted these systems by imposing external legal frameworks that prioritized control, extraction, and hierarchy. Indigenous law was dismissed as informal or illegitimate, while imperial law was enforced through violence and bureaucracy. Over generations, imposed rules became normalized—even when they conflicted with communal ethics. Decolonization here involves remembering that obedience to law is not the same as justice, and that legitimacy comes from consent and restoration, not fear.",
    L3:
      "Empire stabilizes itself through law using recurring patterns:\n\nSANITIZE: Framing coercive control as neutral administration or public safety.\n\nMORALIZE: Casting obedience as virtue and dissent as criminality.\n\nERASE: Eliminating recognition of indigenous legal systems and restorative justice traditions.\n\nPROPERTY: Encoding ownership and exclusion into law, often overriding communal land and resource stewardship.\n\nMILITARIZE: Backing law with force so compliance is secured through threat rather than legitimacy.\n\nLAUNDER_ATTRIB: Attributing inequality to individual behavior instead of legal design and enforcement history.\n\nWhen law becomes invisible, people internalize limits without needing constant enforcement. Decolonization does not require rejecting all law. It requires restoring legal literacy—understanding how rules were formed, who they protect, who they burden, and how they can be changed. When legality is separated from morality, people regain the ability to imagine justice beyond compliance.",
