  core: {
    L1:
      "In mainstream psychology, communication studies, and conflict resolution theory, conflict is understood as a normal outcome of differing needs, values, perceptions, and constraints. Healthy conflict management focuses on clarity, boundaries, empathy, and problem-solving rather than avoidance or domination. Research shows that unresolved conflict often escalates when communication is reactive, personalized, or framed as zero-sum.\n\nModern societies frequently lack effective conflict education. People are trained to debate, defend, or withdraw rather than to listen and repair. Power dynamics—status, resources, authority—further distort communication, making some voices louder and others more cautious. Decolonizing at this level involves shifting from winning arguments to restoring understanding and function.",
    L2:
      "From Afro-Indigenous perspectives, conflict is a signal that balance has been disrupted in relationship. Resolution is not about victory; it is about restoration. Many traditions emphasize councils, mediated dialogue, and collective witnessing to surface truth without humiliation. Accountability is relational, and communication is guided by responsibility to community rather than individual ego.\n\nColonial systems often introduced adversarial models that prioritize punishment, hierarchy, and dominance. Over time, these models shaped interpersonal behavior—conflict becomes a threat to identity rather than an opportunity for alignment. Decolonization here means relearning how to speak and listen from grounded presence. It includes recognizing when conflict is internalized—turned inward as self-criticism or silence—and bringing it back into conscious dialogue.",
    L3:
      "Power distorts conflict through recurring patterns:\n\nMORALIZE: Framing disagreement as a character flaw rather than a difference in perspective or need.\n\nMILITARIZE: Turning conflict into battle language—winning, losing, crushing, defending—so escalation feels justified.\n\nSANITIZE: Ignoring power imbalances and treating all parties as equally positioned.\n\nERASE: Silencing certain voices to preserve comfort or hierarchy.\n\nLAUNDER_ATTRIB: Blaming communication breakdowns on temperament instead of structural pressure.\n\nDecolonizing conflict requires slowing the interaction, naming power dynamics, and restoring mutual recognition. This does not guarantee agreement, but it restores dignity. When conflict is approached as information rather than threat, relationships become sites of growth instead of rupture.",
  },
  practice:
    "Action (20 minutes): Reflect on a recent conflict. Write down: (1) what you needed in that moment, (2) what the other person may have needed, and (3) where power or fear influenced communication. Reimagine one sentence you could have said that named need without accusation.\n\nOptional upgrade: Practice a pause before responding in the next disagreement—three slow breaths before speaking.",
  journal:
    "How were you taught to handle conflict—avoid, dominate, appease, or repair? Which patterns are you ready to unlearn?",
