      "From Afro-Indigenous perspectives, institutions are extensions of community ethics. Councils, age-grade systems, guilds, and spiritual orders distribute authority through role, merit, and responsibility. Leadership is accountable to the people and often rotational. Decision-making emphasizes consensus, restoration, and long-term balance rather than short-term dominance.\n\nColonial disruption replaced these systems with centralized authority and bureaucratic distance. Over time, people were trained to see governance as external rather than participatory. Decolonization here involves reclaiming institutional imagination—designing organizations that reflect shared values, embed care and accountability, and cultivate leadership rather than concentrate power.",
