      "In mainstream philosophy, law, and professional ethics, ethical systems are frameworks for evaluating right action. Concepts such as honesty, fairness, consent, and responsibility are formalized into codes, regulations, and standards. These systems aim to create predictable norms across diverse populations.\n\nHowever, institutional ethics often emphasize compliance over conscience. Rules can be followed while harm persists, and legality can be mistaken for morality. Decolonizing ethics at this level involves recognizing that ethical behavior cannot be reduced to rule-following alone. It requires judgment, context, and willingness to address consequences rather than intentions.",
