    L1:
      "In mainstream psychology, education theory, and organizational studies, discipline is defined as the ability to regulate behavior in service of long-term goals. Healthy discipline strengthens focus, skill acquisition, and resilience. It is internally motivated and adaptive. Domestication, by contrast, describes conditioning that prioritizes compliance over understanding—training individuals to follow rules without context or agency.\n\nModern institutions often blur the two. Schools, workplaces, and social systems reward punctuality, output, and conformity, sometimes without regard for learning, creativity, or well-being. When discipline is externally imposed without meaning, it can produce burnout, passivity, or rebellion rather than mastery. Decolonizing at this level means distinguishing practices that build competence from those that merely enforce control.",
